ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 1
 displays the SEM images of the pure TNAs and GQDs/TNAs. TNAs with hexagonal porous morphology, highly ordered nanotubular structure and smooth surface can be seen in Fig. 1a. These nanotubes are compactly arranged, exhibiting a wall thickness of ca. 30 nm and the inner diameter of ca. 100 nm. The diameter is large enough for the incorporation of GQDs. For the sample IP-GQDs/TNAs (Fig. 1b), there are lots of aggregates distributed on the surface of TNAs and in partial areas, GQDs blocked the entrance of the nanotubes. The surface of the sample EPD-GQDs/TNAs (Fig. 1c) are evenly covered with GQDs. Fig. 1d shows the KEPD-GQDs/TNAs-5 with inner diameter of about 90–95 nm, indicating that the GQDs can be uniformly deposited on the inside tube walls of TNAs. When the deposition time is extended to 15 min, the internal diameters of the KEPD-GQDs/TNAs-15 decrease from 90 to 80 nm (Fig. 3e
). As time increased to 30 min, the inside diameter of the KEPD-GQDs/TNAs-30 inner pore diameter vary from 50 to 105 nm. GQDs densely piled up and there is serious aggregation of GQDs randomly distributed on the local surface of TNAs (Fig. 3f). These results suggest that with the increase of EPD time, the average internal pore diameter of GQDs/TNAs decrease and their distribution uniformity become worse compared to that of KEPD-GQDs/TNAs-5. Fig. 1g is the cross-view image of KEPD-GQDs/TNAs-15. The elemental mapping analysis of KEPD-GQDs/TNAs-15 is shown in Fig. 1h–k. Except for numerous Ti and O, the selected area contains a certain amount of C and N with a uniform distribution density, evident of uniform embedding of GQDs on the inner surface of TNAs.
